1. Introduction 
The purpose of this assignment is to implement a simple UNIX shell in C++ that accepts user 
commands and executes them in separate processes. The shell simulates basic behavior of 
standard UNIX shells such as bash. 
The program uses system calls including: 
● fork() 
● execvp() 
● wait() 
● dup2() 
● pipe() 
● open() 
2. Program Design 
The shell follows this execution flow: 
1. Display prompt osh> 
2. Read user input 
3. Handle built-in commands (exit, !!) 
4. Detect special operators (&, <, >, |) 
5. Create child process using fork() 
6. Execute command using execvp() 
7. Parent waits unless command runs in background 
3. Implemented Features 
3.1 Command Execution 
● The shell parses the input string into arguments. 
● A child process is created using fork(). 
● The child executes the command using execvp(). 
● If execution fails, the shell prints: 
Command not found 
3.2 Background Execution (&) 
If a command ends with &, the shell: 
● Runs the process in background 
● Does not call wait() 
● Immediately returns to the prompt 
Example: 
osh> sleep 5 & 
3.3 Command History (!!) 
The shell stores the most recent command. 
● If user types !!, the previous command is printed and executed again. 
● If no history exists, the shell prints: 
No command history found. 
Example: 
osh> ls -l 
osh> !! 
ls -l 
3.4 Input Redirection (<) 
The shell supports input redirection. 
Example: 
osh> cat < file.txt 
Implementation: 
● open() file in read-only mode 
● dup2() redirects STDIN to file 
● Execute command normally 
3.5 Output Redirection (>) 
The shell supports output redirection. 
Example: 
osh> ls > out.txt 
Implementation: 
● open() file with O_CREAT | O_WRONLY | O_TRUNC 
● dup2() redirects STDOUT to file 
3.6 Pipe (|) — Extra Credit 
The shell supports a single pipe between two commands. 
Example: 
osh> ls -l | wc -l 
Implementation: 
1. Create pipe using pipe(fd) 
2. Fork first child → write to pipe 
3. Fork second child → read from pipe 
4. Parent waits for both processes 
4. Error Handling 
The shell handles errors safely: 
● Invalid command → prints Command not found 
● No history → prints No command history found. 
● File open failure handled properly 
● Program does not crash on invalid input 
● Empty commands are ignored 
